Getting started with Twitter

Twitter

Twitter is an American microblogging and social networking service wheres users post and interact with messages (tweets). As of February 2019, There were 321 million active users. (source: wikipedia)

Applications

  • trending topics by location (world, state, city, etc.)
  • sentiment: customer, brand opinion, organization, etc.
  • reach/popularity of brand, organization, people, etc
  • event detection such as protests, epdemics, pandamics

Tweet Structure

  • User Name: Twitter unique user identification, using the @username syntax.
  • Time Stamp: date/time the tweet was sent
  • Tweet Text: body of the tweet; 140 characters of less
  • Hashtags: proceeded by a # symbol; provides a way for users to communicate with a particular group on twitter (eg: specific event or topic)
  • Links: can be embedded within a tweet
  • Embedded Media: tweets can contain pictures and videos
  • Replies: public replies to tweet posts
  • Retweets: a retweet is the sharing of a tweet with followers
  • Favorites: liking a tweet keeps a history of liked content in your account
  • Latitude/Longitude: geo-location of the tweet; about 1% of all tweets contains coordinate information

Detailed tweet object information: https://developer.twitter.com/en/docs/twitter-api/v1/data-dictionary/overview/tweet-object

Access Tweets Using the Twitter REST API

Benefits

  • open and accessible, even more so than other social media platforms such as Facebook
  • use of hashtags allows easy querying of topics/conversations
  • real time coverage: users can communicate directly in real time
  • popular platform, provides rich source of data mining via API
  • free tier and paid tier

Limitations

  • historical search limited under free account, may not be sufficient
  • free tier allows access to only last 7 days
  • small percentage of tweets include geo tagging makes geo-location analysis more difficult

Twitter Data Access in R

  • twitteR
  • rtweet: a newer package that facilitates importing twitter data into the data.frame

We will be using rtweet R package to access twitter data. Follow the instructions below to get started with Twitter in R

  1. Obtain/using access tokens: https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/rtweet/vignettes/auth.html
    Use Access token/secret method for personal Twitter token
  2. Collecting Twitter Data: https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/rtweet/vignettes/intro.html

Example of using Twitter

libraries

# twitter library 
library(rtweet)

# plotting and pipes - tidyverse
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr, warn.conflicts = FALSE)
options(dplyr.summarise.inform = FALSE) # Suppress summarise info

# text mining library
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(tidyverse)) # suppress startup message

# date/time libaray
library(lubridate, warn.conflicts = FALSE)

Obtaining and using access tokens

See: https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/rtweet/vignettes/auth.html
Use Access token/secret method for personal Twitter token

authenticate

if (tokenOk==FALSE) {
  ## authenticate via web browser
  token <- create_token(
    app = "gguSentiment",
    consumer_key = api_key,
    consumer_secret = api_secret_key,
    access_token = access_token,
    access_secret = access_token_secret)
}

## for subsequent sessions, check to see if the token is loaded

search_tweets()

returns tweets matching a search query, from the past 7 days only and max of 18000 per request

search for 500 tweets using the #rstats hashtag

  • a retweet is when someone shares someone elses tweet. To ignore all retweets, set include_rts argument to FALSE.
  • lang argument filters tweet by language, default is English (en)
rstats_tweets <- search_tweets(q = "#rstats",       # query
                               n = 500,             # number to return
                               include_rts = FALSE) # don't include retweets

where are these users from?

# how many locations are represented
length(unique(users$location))
## [1] 302
# plot these users
users %>%
  ggplot(aes(location)) +
  geom_bar() + coord_flip() +
      labs(x = "Count",
      y = "Location",
      title = "Twitter users - unique locations")

Theres too much data. Lets sort by count and just plot the top locations using slice_max function.

users %>%
  count(location, sort = TRUE)  %>%               # count location by users
  mutate(location = reorder(location, n))  %>%    # sort
  slice_max( order_by=location, n = 10) %>%       # rows with top 10 location
  
  ggplot(aes(x = location, y = n)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
      labs(x = "Count",
      y = "Location",
      title = "Where Twitter users are from - unique locations")

There are some NA or no data values, we can remove those with drop_na

users$location[users$location==""] <- NA # replace blanks with NA

df=users %>%
  count(location, sort = TRUE)  %>%               # count location by users
  mutate(location = reorder(location, n))  %>%    # sort
  slice_max( order_by=location, n = 10)   %>%     # rows with top 10 location
  drop_na()
  
# plot    
ggplot(df, aes(x = location, y = n)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
      labs(x = "Count",
      y = "Location",
      title = "Where Twitter users are from - unique locations")

returns tweets by a specific user, up to 3200 tweets

ts_plot()

plot the frequency of tweets for each user over time. The ts_plot() function allows us to plot the frequency of tweets over various time intervals (e.g.secs, mins, hours, days, weeks, months, years)

gt_timelines %>%
  #filter(created_at > "2020-02-01") %>%
  group_by(screen_name) %>%
  ts_plot("days") +
  geom_point() +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    legend.title = element_blank(),
    legend.position = "bottom",
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold")) +
    labs(x = NULL, y = NULL,
      title = "Frequency of Twitter statuses posted by rstudio and tidyversetweets",
      subtitle = "Twitter status (tweet) counts aggregated by day"
  )

group by screen name and plot each time series

# weeks
gt_timelines %>%
  group_by(screen_name) %>%
  ts_plot("weeks")

# group by screen name and is_retweet
gt_timelines %>%
  group_by(screen_name, is_retweet) %>%
  ts_plot("days")

filtering tweets
1. -filter (original tweets)
2. -filter:retweets (excludes retweets, eg: is_retweet)
3. -filter:quote (excludes quoted tweets, eg: is_quote)
4. -filter:replies (excludes reply tweets, eg: reply_to_screen_name )
5. min_faves (filters tweets by min number of favorite)
6. min_retweets (filter tweets by min number of retweets)

more info: https://developer.twitter.com/en/docs/twitter-api/v1/rules-and-filtering/overview/standard-operators

da_tweets = search_tweets("data analysis -filter:retweets",  # exclude retweets
                          n=200)
